            "sample": [
              "\"robustness\": \"standard\",",
              "  \"signals\": {",
              "    \"iteration\": 2,",
              "    \"idea\": \"Fix how track-level settings and clip-level overrides interact.\\n\\nCURRENT PROBLEM: Track scale (e.g. 0.95) creates a CSS transform scale() wrapper around all clips on that track. When a user drags a clip to set x/y position, the track scale acts as a hard boundary - you can't move the clip to the edges because the scaled-down container clips the content. The track scale and clip positioning are fighting each other.\\n\\nCORRECT MENTAL MODEL: Track settings are DEFAULTS that clips inherit. Clip-level settings OVERRIDE track settings, they don't stack on top. Specifically:\\n\\n1. SCALE: Track scale=0.95 means 'by default, show clips at 95% zoom'. If a clip has its own scale/size override, use THAT instead, not track_scale * clip_scale. The clip override replaces the track default.\\n\\n2. POSITION: Track scale affects where content appears (centered, scaled down). But if a clip has x/y set, those coordinates should be in the full composition space (1280x720), and the clip should render at those absolute coordinates regardless of track scale.\\n\\n3. FIT: Track fit=contain means 'by default, letterbox clips'. If a clip has explicit width/height, use those instead.\\n\\nThe key insight: track settings define the DEFAULT rendering for clips that have no overrides. Once a clip has ANY position/size override, it should render in absolute composition space, completely bypassing track scale/fit.\\n\\nIMPLEMENTATION: The current approach in TimelineRenderer.tsx wraps ALL clips in a div with transform:scale(trackScale). This is wrong because it scales even overridden clips. Instead:\\n- Clips WITHOUT overrides: render inside the scaled track wrapper (inheriting track defaults)\\n- Clips WITH overrides: render in absolute composition space, bypassing the track wrapper entirely\\n\\nThe OverlayEditor canvas interaction should always work in composition space (1280x720). When a user drags a clip that was previously using track defaults, it should initialize the override from the clip's current visual position (accounting for the track scale) and then let the user freely position it anywhere in composition space.\\n\\nALSO FIX: The overlay drag box alignment - it needs to correctly show where the clip IS (accounting for track scale for non-overridden clips) and where it WILL BE (in composition space for overridden clips).\","
            ]
          },
          {
            "id": "a4a4f984c29b1bbc",
            "distinct_files": 2,
            "window_size": 13,
            "locations": [
